{
  "id": "infiniflow_ragflow_15438",
  "repo_name": "infiniflow/ragflow",
  "repo_url": "https://github.com/infiniflow/ragflow",
  "base_commit": "cd18cfab79578bc0e2797b2614afde44f1e0a411",
  "pr_number": 15438,
  "issue_number": 15437,
  "issue_title": "SSRF in markdown document parser: uploaded image references trigger server-side requests to internal/metadata endpoints",
  "issue_body": "## Summary\n\nWhen a markdown document (`.md` / `.markdown` / `.mdx`) is uploaded to a knowledge base, RAGFlow parses out every image reference in the document and fetches it **server-side with no SSRF validation**. Any authenticated user who can upload a document can therefore make the RAGFlow server issue HTTP requests to arbitrary internal services and cloud-metadata endpoints \u2014 a classic server-side request forgery (SSRF) primitive.\n\n## Affected code\n\n`rag/app/naive.py` \u2014 `Markdown.load_images_from_urls`:\n\n```python\nif url.startswith((\"http://\", \"https://\")):\n    response = requests.get(url, stream=True, timeout=30)\n    if response.status_code == 200 and response.headers.get(\"Content-Type\", \"\").startswith(\"image/\"):\n        img_obj = Image.open(BytesIO(response.content)).convert(\"RGB\")\n```\n\nThe `url` values come straight from image references extracted from the uploaded document (`extract_image_urls_with_lines`). There is no scheme/host/IP validation and no DNS pinning.\n\nThis path is **not optional**: markdown chunking always calls it. In the same file:\n\n```python\nelif re.search(r\"\\.(md|markdown|mdx)$\", filename, re.IGNORECASE):\n    ...\n    sections, tables, section_images = markdown_parser(\n        filename, binary, separate_tables=False,\n        delimiter=parser_config.get(\"delimiter\", \"\\n!?;\u3002\uff1b\uff01\uff1f\"),\n        return_section_images=True,      # -> load_images_from_urls() for every image ref\n    )\n```\n\n## Impact\n\nAn attacker uploads a markdown file containing image references that point at internal targets, e.g.:\n\n```markdown\n![x](http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/)\n![x](http://127.0.0.1:9380/)\n![x](http://internal-service.cluster.local:6379/)\n```\n\nWhen the document is parsed/chunked, the RAGFlow server makes a GET request to each URL from **inside the trusted network**. This enables:\n\n- Reading cloud instance metadata / temporary credentials (AWS/GCP/Azure metadata service).\n- Probing and reaching internal-only services (databases, caches, admin ports) that are not exposed externally.\n\nThe `Content-Type` / `image/` check only decides whether the response body is decoded as an image \u2014 the outbound request (the SSRF itself) always fires, so blind SSRF, internal port-scanning, and metadata hits succeed regardless of the response.\n\n**Authentication required:** any user with permission to upload a document to a knowledge base.\n\n## Why this is clearly a defect (not intended behavior)\n\nThe project already ships a shared SSRF guard, `common/ssrf_guard.py` (`assert_url_is_safe` / `assert_host_is_safe` + DNS pinning), and has applied it to virtually every other user-controlled fetch site \u2014 the web crawler (`agent/tools/crawler.py`), SearXNG tool (`agent/tools/searxng.py`), RSS connector (`common/data_source/rss_connector.py`), MCP API, document API, file service, and OAuth avatar download. The markdown image fetch is simply a site that was missed by that hardening effort.\n\n## Suggested fix\n\nValidate every image URL with `common.ssrf_guard.assert_url_is_safe` and DNS-pin it before connecting; follow redirects manually so each redirect target is re-validated (closing the DNS-rebinding / redirect-bypass window), mirroring the existing pattern in `common/data_source/rss_connector.py`. URLs that fail validation should simply be skipped (logged), exactly like any other unreachable image, so legitimate public images are unaffected.\n\n## Environment\n\n- Component: document parsing pipeline (`rag/app/naive.py`)\n- Trigger: upload of any `.md` / `.markdown` / `.mdx` document to a knowledge base\n- Affected versions: current `main` (HEAD at time of report)",
  "merged_at": "2026-06-16T10:54:55.000Z",
